        "text": "were glad",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; glad, because they saw the prospect of the accomplishment of their wishes; glad, because it was \"one of the twelve\" who covenanted to betray him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "They promised to give him money.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " St. Matthew (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") tells us the amount, namely, thirty pieces of silver, according to the prophecy of Zechariah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Zechariah 11:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), to which St. Matthew evidently refers. These pieces of silver were shekels of the sanctuary, worth about three shillings each. This would make the whole amount about £4 10s. of our money; less than half the value of the precious ointment with which Mary had anointed him. Some commentators, however, think that this was only an instalment of what they promised him if he completed his treasonable design. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "How he might conveniently deliver him unto them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " St. Luke (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 22:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") explains this by saying, \"in the absence of the multitude;\" that is, when the people were not about him, and when he was in private with his disciples. And so he betrayed him at night, when he was alone with his disciples in the Garden of Gethsemane. Mark 14:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
